[[File:Barcelona MNAC P1290784.JPG|thumb|right|The Arlanza [[Griffon|gryphon]], [[fresco]] transferred to canvas, 189.5 × 322 cm, c. 1210, [[National Art Museum of Catalonia|MNAC]], Barcelona]]
The '''paintings from Arlanza''' are a set of [[fresco]]s belonging to the [[mural painting|mural decoration]] of a [[Benedictine]] [[monastery of San Pedro de Arlanza]], in the [[Province of Burgos]], [[Castile and León]], Spain, dating to around 1210, and now dispersed among a number of collections.  The Spanish government began to detach and sell sections of the frescos in the 19th century, though less exciting sections remain ''in situ''.  The largest group of six major fragments has moved to the [[National Art Museum of Catalonia]] of [[Barcelona]] in 1943.  Most of the [[Romanesque art|Romanesque mural painting]] that has survived is of religious subjects, but there was also find decoration of a courtly or profane nature in large monastic centres, such as Arlanza in [[Kingdom of Castile|Castile]], and these fragments represent especially rare survivals.<ref>[http://art.mnac.cat/fitxatecnica.html;jsessionid=1e5b501d514ceac21bf35f4a14523af9fd0144abc5a1f3ed10e00fa78c2c9cbd?inventoryNumber=040142-000Catalog entry at the MNAC website]</ref>  According to C.R. Dodwell, the "imposing" Arlanza paintings are "endowed with all the power and grandeur of Romanesque at its best".<ref>Dodwell, 268</ref>

== Description ==
The ten very large animals and other subjects from the world of [[heraldry]]<ref>Dodwell describes them as "over life-size", somewhat begging the question in the case of the dragon and other mythical beasts</ref> come from the [[chapter house]] or a room above,<ref>Sources are oddly variable on this</ref> on the lowest floor of the so-called ''Torre del Tesoro'' (Treasury Tower), and are inspired by illuminated [[bestiary|bestiaries]], with the basic landscape backgrounds that are often seen in these.  The Barcelona group includes a [[Griffon|gryphon]], a legendary creature with the body of a lion and the head and wings of an eagle, in a watchful pose. The MNAC has 5 more fragments from the same decorative group. There are other panels of a lion and a dragon, now at [[The Cloisters]] in New York,<ref>[http://www.metmuseum.org/Collections/search-the-collections/70011540 Cloisters lion]</ref> one at the [[Harvard University]] [[Fogg Art Museum]],<ref>[http://www.harvardartmuseums.org/collection/detail.dot?objectid=1938.124&globalSearchText=Arlanza Fogg Art Museum fragment]{{dead link|date=March 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> and another in a private collection.

The style of the paintings in Arlanza is related to other Spanish works of around 1200, especially the frescos from the [[Monastery of Santa María de Sigena]] (also in MNAC, Barcelona), which are clearly influenced by English [[illuminated manuscript]] miniature painting, something that can be seen in the refinement and the precision of the motifs, combined with their monumental nature.<ref>[http://art.mnac.cat/fitxatecnica.html;jsessionid=1e5b501d514ceac21bf35f4a14523af9fd0144abc5a1f3ed10e00fa78c2c9cbd?inventoryNumber=040142-000Catalog entry at the MNAC website]; also see Cloisters</ref>  The Sigena frescos, which are probably actually largely by English artists, namely some of the team who illuminated the [[Winchester Bible]],<ref>Dodwell, 372-373, and Oakeshott throughout</ref> also contain a very similar gryphon and lion,<ref>Oakeshott: Gryphon, figures 207 (Arlanza) and 208 (Sigena), Sigena lion figure 42; the Sigena gryphon, after fire damage, can be seen at right [[:File:Barcelona MNAC P1290802.JPG|in this photo]].</ref> and are possibly by the same principal artist.<ref>Dodwell, 268</ref>  The Arlanza fragments in New York still include their section of the black and white [[frieze]] with more figures including fabulous beasts running below the large [[polychrome]] animals.

